\begin_layout Section*
Reviewer 1 - Referee report: AJAE MS 19030, “Information and communication
 technologies (ICTs) to provide agricultural advice to smallholder farmers:
 Experimental evidence from Uganda.” 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper presents the results of an RCT designed to measure the impact
 of agricultural extension information for smallholder maize farmers in
 eastern Uganda provided in three ways using ICT: (i) informational videos
 shown to farmers (in-person on a tablet, twice), (ii) an invitation to
 an IVR-based information hotline that farmers could call on demand, and
 (iii) reminder SMS messages about agricultural practices and the hotline.
 The intervention was incremental---other than a pure control group, treated
 farmers received (i), (i) and (ii), or (i), (ii), and (iii) (i.e.
 no farmers received an invitation to the IVR-based hotline without also
 seeing the videos).
 The authors find that farmers retain the new information provided to them
 in the videos and that they change their behavior accordingly, leading
 to an increase in yields of 10 percent.
 They find no increased impact of inviting farmers to the IVR-based hotline
 nor of the reminder SMS messages.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Perhaps the greatest strength of this study is the care which the authors
 put into what information was provided to farmers and when.
 This is evident in the description of the process by which the authors
 determined what information to provide farmers and how to package it.
 It is no surprise to me given this care that the information was valuable
 and that farmers absorbed it and some acted on it.
 As such, I believe this paper presents a clear contribution in how agricultural
 extension information provision, if done carefully, can have an impact.
 This is especially important given how split the literature is on the possible
 impacts of information provision for farmers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the same time, perhaps the two greatest weaknesses of this study are
 both features of the design that are fixed---the incremental design rather
 than a true test of supply-driven versus demand-driven information and
 the short-term nature of the outcomes.
 In the former case, the authors (I believe rightfully) highlight the tension
 between supply-driven information provision (experts deciding what information
 farmers would benefit from and giving it to them) and demand-driven (making
 information available but letting farmers seek out what information they
 want when they want it).
 But then the incremental design of the study prohibits the authors from
 actually testing supply- vs demand-driven information provision in a meaningful
 way.
 The challenge with the short-term nature of the outcomes is that the authors
 find increased yield per acre of land for treated farmers relative to control
 but no increase in total maize output and, at the same time, changes in
 inputs.
 We are left not knowing if households are actually better off in the short
 term, or even better off in the sense that they may have made changes that
 come at a cost in the short-term but are worthwhile in the medium-/long-term.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While these two weaknesses are fixed, I believe the authors can better address
 them: 
