\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
We then discuss a particular concern with our measure of compliance.
 In particular, we suspect that LATE in our context would overestimate the
 impact of the IVR.
 The reason is that our indicator of take up of the intervention is likely
 to be measured with significant error.
 In particular, our indicator of compliance is taken from the IVR system
 log, where recorded telephone numbers are matched to phone numbers that
 were recorded during baseline data collection.
 This indicator is likely to severely under-report true compliance, as encourage
d farmers may use different phones to call the IVR.
 This is illustrated by the fact that about 430 unique calls were made to
 the system, representing about 18 percent of encouraged households, hence
 almost doubling compliance.
 Using our measure of compliance, we can not maintain that the independence
 assumption holds, as some of the potential outcomes are directly determined
 by the instrument.
 The problem becomes clear when we think about LATE as the Wald estimator
 that scales the ITT by compliance.
 In our case, the ITT will be estimated on the basis of all 430 farmers
 that called in.
 Our measure of compliance will force all the impact of the treatment to
 work through the 214 households that show up in the IVR log and could be
 identified in the baseline, which in the case of a positive impact would
 lead to an overestimate of the impact of the treatment on compliers.
 It is well know that especially in the context of a weak first stage the
 bias can become extremely large 
